                            <comment id="17602904" author="janhoy" created="Sun, 11 Sep 2022 19:09:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I reproduced it locally. Since Solr reads this env var directly in Java code, it needs to be exported from the shell for the var to be visible in the Java process. But bin/solr script sources solr.in.sh, which is not an export.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Simplest solution is to modify the example commented line in solr.in.sh to use &lt;b&gt;export&lt;/b&gt;. Tested it and that works. Perhaps that is a good enough solution. Else, we&apos;d need to modify bin/solr to explicitly pass SOLR_MODULES as -Dsolr.modules as we do with the other vars.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17602950" author="thomas.woeckinger" created="Mon, 12 Sep 2022 05:42:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;From a consistent point of view i would prefer the last solution. I think it does not make sense to handle this entry differently compared to the others.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17602954" author="thomas.woeckinger" created="Mon, 12 Sep 2022 05:56:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;If you like i can have look (i think the change would be rather easy) and provide a pull request.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17603051" author="thomas.woeckinger" created="Mon, 12 Sep 2022 11:34:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=janhoy&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;janhoy&quot;&gt;janhoy&lt;/a&gt;&#160; I added pull request but have overseen yours.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I changed both startup scripts, but if you really want to remove the whole option from solr.in.sh the PR is obsolete.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17603434" author="janhoy" created="Tue, 13 Sep 2022 07:45:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I abandoned my workaround PR, and approved your PR which I believe is a better solution. Will merge soon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My approach with adding &quot;export&quot; can be used as a workaround for 9.0.0 users.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17603435" author="thomas.woeckinger" created="Tue, 13 Sep 2022 07:49:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Is there already a schedule for the next Solr release either 9.0.1 or 9.1.0?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17603713" author="janhoy" created="Tue, 13 Sep 2022 18:33:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;There is never a schedule. A new release is started when a committer sees a user need for a feature/bugfix and volunteer as RM. There will not be a 9.0.1, the next release will be 9.1.0.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
